                <note rend="inline" type="source">348a.116 M 82/22</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Senator
                            <persName type="to">Reed Smoot</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-01-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 22, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Senator Smoot</hi>: I wish to refer to my letter of
                    August 10, 1922,<note n="43" xml:id="d205fn43">Not printed.</note> relating to
                    the refusal of the South African railway authorities to allow reduced rates to
                    elders of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints.</p>
                <p>I have now received a despatch from the American Consulate General at Cape
                        Town<note n="43" xml:id="d205fn44">Not printed.</note> stating that as a
                    result of the Consulate General’s representations the South African Railway
                    Administration has now recognized the elders of the Church of Jesus Christ of
                    Latter Day Saints as entitled to the usual travel concessions granted to
                    Ministers of the Gospel and Missionaries under the new regulations which were
                    effective January 1, 1923.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
